From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: CamNode Build System <build@vidala-labs.com>
Date: Wed, 9 Apr 2026 13:00:00 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] pinctrl: intel: geminilake: preserve PCIe interrupt state
 during init

Skip GPIO interrupt masking for pin group containing PCIE_WAKE and
PCIE_CLKREQ signals (pins 32-63 in North community) to prevent
disrupting PCIe device enumeration.

On HP Gemini Lake devices, the pinctrl-geminilake driver probe occurs
early via subsys_initcall(), potentially during PCIe bus enumeration.
The generic intel_gpio_irq_init() masks all GPIO interrupts, which can
interfere with PCIe wake and clock request signaling, causing WiFi and
other PCIe devices to fail enumeration.

This patch identifies the North community (uid "2") and skips interrupt
masking for pin group 1 (pins 32-63) which contains:
- PCIE_WAKE0_B through PCIE_WAKE3_B (pins 40-43)
- PCIE_CLKREQ0_B through PCIE_CLKREQ3_B (pins 44-47)

Background:
The Gemini Lake pinctrl driver is needed to provide GPIOLIB_IRQCHIP for
I2C-HID touchscreen interrupt support. However, enabling it breaks WiFi
on some HP devices with Realtek RTL8821CE adapters. This patch allows
both touchscreen GPIO interrupts and PCIe device functionality to coexist.

Signed-off-by: CamNode Build System <build@vidala-labs.com>
---
 drivers/pinctrl/intel/pinctrl-intel.c | 26 +++++++++++++++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 25 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/drivers/pinctrl/intel/pinctrl-intel.c b/drivers/pinctrl/intel/pinctrl-intel.c
--- a/drivers/pinctrl/intel/pinctrl-intel.c
+++ b/drivers/pinctrl/intel/pinctrl-intel.c
@@ -1294,12 +1294,36 @@ static irqreturn_t intel_gpio_irq(int irq, void *data)

 static void intel_gpio_irq_init(struct intel_pinctrl *pctrl)
 {
+	const struct intel_pinctrl_soc_data *soc = pctrl->soc;
 	const struct intel_community *community;

 	for_each_intel_pin_community(pctrl, community) {
 		void __iomem *reg, *is;
 		unsigned int gpp;

 		for (gpp = 0; gpp < community->ngpps; gpp++) {
+			/*
+			 * Gemini Lake North community workaround:
+			 * Skip interrupt masking for pin group 1 (pins 32-63)
+			 * which contains PCIe wake and clock request signals.
+			 *
+			 * On HP Gemini Lake devices, masking these pins during
+			 * early boot (subsys_initcall) can disrupt PCIe device
+			 * enumeration, particularly WiFi adapters.
+			 *
+			 * North community is identified by uid "2" and has:
+			 * - gpp_size = 32 (pins grouped 0-31, 32-63, 64-79)
+			 * - Pin group 1 (gpp=1) contains PCIE_WAKE0-3_B (40-43)
+			 *   and PCIE_CLKREQ0-3_B (44-47)
+			 */
+			if (soc->uid && strcmp(soc->uid, "2") == 0 &&
+			    community->gpp_size == 32 && gpp == 1) {
+				dev_info(pctrl->dev,
+					 "Preserving PCIe interrupt state for pin group %u (pins %u-%u)\n",
+					 gpp, community->pin_base + (gpp * 32),
+					 community->pin_base + (gpp * 32) + 31);
+				continue;
+			}
+
 			reg = community->regs + community->ie_offset + gpp * 4;
 			is = community->regs + community->is_offset + gpp * 4;

--
2.43.0
